Description of pupa. Male (
Fig. 6
). Length 42.2 mm . Width at pronotum 20 mm . Body shape elongate, oval, stout. Color dark reddish orange. Entire body with fine, velvety-gold vestiture.

Natural History . The life cycle of the species is one year. The pupal stage lasts from January to March. Adults have been taken primarily at lights at night. They had been observed flying between 18 : 30 to 05:00. The reproductive behavior of this species is similar to that found in other Oryctini (
Neita et al . 2006
). The sexually mature male makes a gallery in the soil about 60 cm deep. Mating occurs outside the gallery, followed by the death of the male. The larvae feed on decomposing organic matter and have been observed feeding in crops, such as the roots of potato, corn, ornamental flowers, and different types of grasses ( JCNM , personal observation).
